{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59359fc1-7953-427a-83d0-f915d8e47624","content":"There's no relevant documentation in this repository. Here's the general guidance for recovering a crash dump on macOS for a NativeAOT app without `createdump`:\n\n**On macOS, use the system's built-in crash reporting:**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check `/cores/`** — macOS writes core files to `/cores/core.<pid>`. Ensure the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n3. **Check Apple crash logs** — macOS also writes `.ips` crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `lldb`** to analyze the core file:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If core dumps are still not appearing**, check SIP (System Integrity Protection) restrictions and ensure your binary is not code-signed with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement disabled. You may need to re-sign with that entitlement for local debugging.\n\n**Key note:** NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR component), so the macOS system-level core dump mechanism is the expected path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28ec6ec3-ea7a-4861-81d1-73f96e078f4f","outputTokens":350,"requestId":"C3C3:86E8:1CF892D:209351C:6A07C2B6"},"id":"7d2185cb-3ef5-418c-b5a5-f10c62f1bddf","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:03.249Z","parentId":"fba992b9-3daa-421b-b87b-d4808d1f3565"}
